SYMPTOM_TEXT: After getting Hep A vaccination on 12/20, went home and son took a nap, he woke up and would not walk.  After 48 hours of him not walking at all and then I noticed swelling in his left knee (same leg as vaccine) went back to Dr's office, Dr took blood work and x-rays.  Dr spoke to Ortho Nurse Practitioner and they advised to give Motrin thru the holiday weekend.  My son began to walk, with a bad limp on Fri 12/23.  On Tues 12/27, went to see the Ortho Nurse Practitioner (b/c Dr was on vac), she did more blood work.  On Wed received a call from my Ped. & she advised me to go to hospital.  They did more blood work, ultrasound, and x-rays.  Then drew fluid from knee.  After that test came back they admitted us due to a bacterial infection in the knee.  My son had surgery the next day to flush out the knee.  Son is doing much better, still walking with a limp.  They were unable to determine what kind of bacteria caused the problem.
LAB_DATA: Blood work to check CRP and SEDS, X-rays, Ultrasound, drained fluid from knee, tested bacteria

A 21-year-old male patient received TRUMEMBA; (Batch/Lot: N16808; Exp: 30Jul2017) at 0.5 ml single intramuscular in left deltoid as prevention of meningo B on 29Sep2016 at 16:30. On the same day he received also the tenth dose of influenza vaccine quadrivalent (Manufacturer: Sanofi; Lot #: U1678AB) intramuscular in right deltoid for immunization. Concomitant medications included DEXTROAMPHETAMINE from 26Sep (unspecified year) for ADHD at 5mg 3x/day. On an unspecified date, after receiving suspect vaccines, the patient developed body aches and severe back pain which caused a severe burning pain and numbness of his legs. No adverse effects were reported. Additionally, on an unknown date (reported as "recently"), some rubber was going into vial upon entering vial with blunt needle cannula on the LIQUID PEDVAXHIB vial with lot # M014927, so the vial was not used. A product quality complaint (PQC) was filled. Follow up information has been received from the registered nurse on 15-DEC-2016. The nurse reported that the vaccines got contaminated with the rubber, so they did not administered the vaccines to the patients. It was indicated that no adverse event was actually involved in the previously reported experience. Therefore, MARRS# 1610USA010243 is being deleted from  our files on haemophilus b conjugate vaccine (meningococcal protein conjugate). Additional information is not expected as all follow up has been received. Reporter, event and narrative were updated. Sender's Comments: MERCK 1610USA010243: Mfr number.

This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of cleft palate in a neonate. The mother received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden. The pregnancy resulted in a live neonate with a congenital anomaly. The neonate was diagnosed with cleft palate. Serious criteria included GSK medically significant, congenital anomaly and other: serious per reporter. Additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure and live birth. The outcome of cleft palate was unknown. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure (unknown) and live birth (unknown). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the cleft palate may have been caused by Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden. Additional information was provided. This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in this literature article and described the occurrence of cleft palate incomplete in a neonate of unspecified gender whose mother was vaccinated with unspecified seasonal inactivated influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) during pregnancy. The patient's mother was a part of the study that assessed the safety of seasonal inactivated influenza vaccines (IIV) and live attenuated influenza vaccines (LAIVs) in pregnant women and their infants whose reports were submitted to Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) during 2010-2016. No information on patient's medical history or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient's mother received unspecified seasonal inactivated influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosages unknown; batch number not provided). Subsequently, the patient was exposed to the vaccine in utero. On an unspecified date between 1 July 2010 and 6 May 2016, an unknown period after maternal vaccine exposure, the patient developed cleft palate incomplete. This case has been considered serious as per the authors. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not reported. The authors did not comment on the relationship between cleft palate incomplete and unspecified seasonal inactivated influenza vaccine. However the authors stated, "VAERS also generally cannot determine whether a vaccine caused an AE." The authors concluded that "During the study period 2010-2016, the average annual number of VAERS reports following IIV in pregnancy decreased compared with the 2009-2010 pandemic period but remained higher than prior to the pandemic. Similar to the 2009-2010 period, no new or unexpected patterns in maternal or fetal outcomes were observed during 2010-2016. Maternal influenza vaccination benefits both the mother and the infant, protecting both from influenza disease. Given that the antigenic composition of these vaccines usually changes each season, the CDC and FDA will continue to monitor the safety of influenza vaccines in pregnant women." This is 1 of the 12 valid cases reported in the same literature article.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in a literature article and described the occurrence of birth defects in a neonate. The mother received Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden. The pregnancy resulted in a live neonate with a congenital anomaly. The neonate was diagnosed with birth defects. Serious criteria included congenital anomaly and other: serious per reporter. Additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure and live birth. The outcome of birth defects was unknown. The outcome(s) of the additional event(s) included maternal vaccine exposure (unknown) and live birth (unknown). The investigator considered that there was a reasonable possibility that the birth defects may have been caused by Flu Seasonal QIV Dresden. Additional information was provided. This retrospective pregnancy case was reported in this literature article and described the occurrence of multiple birth defects in a neonate of unspecified gender whose mother was vaccinated with unspecified seasonal inactivated influenza vaccine (manufacturer unknown) during pregnancy. The patient's mother was a part of the study that assessed the safety of seasonal inactivated influenza vaccines (IIV) and live attenuated influenza vaccines (LAIVs) in pregnant women and their infants whose reports were submitted to Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System (VAERS) during 2010-2016. No information on patient's medical history or family history or concurrent condition or concomitant medication was provided. On an unspecified date, the patient's mother received unspecified seasonal inactivated influenza vaccine (administration route and site unspecified; dosages unknown; batch number not provided). Subsequently, the patient was exposed to the vaccine in utero. On an unspecified date between 1 July 2010 and 6 May 2016, an unknown period after maternal vaccine exposure, the patient developed multiple birth defects. This case has been considered serious as per the authors. Treatment was unknown. The outcome of the event was not reported. The authors did not comment on the relationship between multiple birth defects and unspecified seasonal inactivated influenza vaccine. However the authors stated, "VAERS also generally cannot determine whether a vaccine caused an AE." The authors concluded that "During the study period 2010-2016, the average annual number of VAERS reports following IIV in pregnancy decreased compared with the 2009-2010 pandemic period but remained higher than prior to the pandemic. Similar to the 2009-2010 period, no new or unexpected patterns in maternal or fetal outcomes were observed during 2010-2016. Maternal influenza vaccination benefits both the mother and the infant, protecting both from influenza disease. Given that the antigenic composition of these vaccines usually changes each season, the CDC and FDA will continue to monitor the safety of influenza vaccines in pregnant women." This is 1 of the 12 valid cases reported in the same literature article.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This literature marketed report was received from the authors of a published article. This report refers to a male patient of unknown age. On an unknown date, the patient was vaccinated with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) for prophylaxis. The patient had immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP) post-splenectomy who presented with fever, vomiting, diarrhea, increased white count and drop in platelets to 58. He was admitted to the ICU and required vasopressors for hemodynamic instability. He had streptococcus pneumonia bacteremia even after immunization with pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) before his splenectomy (Vaccination failure and Pneumococcal sepsis). His lower extremities developed purpura fulminans-like rash possibly secondary to streptococcus pneumonia bacteremia and gangrenous wounds on lower extremities which warranted amputation due to concern for non-viable necrotic tissue. He was later found to have common variable immune deficiency (CVID) with low levels of IgG, IgA and IgM in his blood on evaluation for recurrent respiratory tract infections. It was reported that, ITP could be the presenting symptom of CVID and hence it may not be unreasonable to test for immunoglobulin levels on diagnosis of ITP. In this patient, inadequate response to the pneumococcal vaccine, polyvalent (23-valent) (manufacturer unknown) due to co-existing CVID may have resulted in overwhelming pneumococcal sepsis. Adequate gamma-globulin replacements before proceeding with vaccinations could have helped. At the time of this report, the outcome of the events was unknown. Upon internal review, event pneumococcal sepsis was determined to be medically significant. Additional information has been requested.
CUR_ILL: Immune thrombocytopenic purpura; Immunodeficiency common variable

September 30, 2016-About 4:00 PM I received the FLUZONE HIGH-DOSE vaccine at Pharmacy. Within an hour my arm was sore and a lump had developed around the injection site. The soreness interrupted my sleep and worsened throughout the night. October 1, 2016-After getting up I had increasing discomfort in both arms and my lower back and hips. It was the day of our town-wide garage sale and lower-back pain caused walking to become so painful that I returned home and went to bed, where I remained for two days. I developed a fever and aching pain around and behind my right eye. I was mildly nauseated and had little appetite. October 2, 2016-The pain intensified, I could not sleep because of the back, leg and pain in both shoulder. My joints became so stiff that I could not bend over, step into the tub or dress myself. My fatigue was so overwhelming that I could barely move and I felt depressed. October 4, 2016-The fever went away, my eye stopped hurting. But the pain continued, and I had cramps in my legs. Extreme fatigue and depression continued. I assumed it was a reaction to the shot which would run its course. Yet it continued, the pain altering somewhat in its location and severity over the next two weeks. Friday, October 14, 2016-I called Dr.'s office and described my symptom to the Nurse, asking her to relay them to Dr. His response was that my symptoms were most likely a flu-shot reaction and instructed me to take TYLENOL and check in on Monday, October 17. On Monday, October 17, I felt for the first time as if the symptoms were measurably improved, and informed Dr's office of that. I was preparing for a trip north which would last for at least two weeks. Unfortunately the improvement I experienced was simply the beginning of a pattern in which the symptoms appear to be dissipating only to return stronger than ever. Sleep was nearly impossible as pain in both shoulders and my hips and back was worsened with each movement. The stiffness and muscle soreness would appear to be lessening for several days only to return in full force, once again flattening me with pain, restricted motion, fatigue, depression and generalized discomfort. I cut my northern visit short to return as I was now concerned that whatever was causing my symptoms might be degenerative. November 18, 2016-I had an appointment with Dr. He performed an evaluation, ordered blood work, and prescribed Prednisone. The Prednisone alleviated my symptoms. November 28, 2016-Appointment with Dr. who diagnosed my condition as Polymyalgia Rheumatica. I am to return to his office for a follow-up on January 9, 2017.
LAB_DATA: See attached lab results and doctor's note

Initial unsolicited report received from the literature on 31-Dec-2016. The following is verbatim from the article: Abstract: Introduction: This is the 33rd Annual Report. As of 1 January 2015, 55 of the nation's poison centers (PCs) uploaded case data automatically to database. The upload interval was 9.52 [7.40, 13.6] (median [25%, 75%]) minutes, creating a near real-time national exposure and information database and surveillance system. Methods: We analyzed the case data tabulating specific indices from the database. The methodology was similar to that of previous years. Where changes were introduced, the differences are identified. Poison center cases with medical outcomes of death were evaluated by a team of medical and clinical toxicologist reviewers using an ordinal scale of 1-6 to assess the Relative Contribution to Fatality (RCF) of the exposure. Results: In 2015, 2,792,130 closed encounters were logged by NPDS: 2,168,371 human exposures, 55,516 animal exposures, 560,467 information calls, 7657 human confirmed non-exposures, and 119 animal confirmed non-exposures. PCs also made 2,695,699 follow-up calls in 2015. Total encounters showed a 3.42% decline from 2014, while healthcare facility (HCF) human exposure cases increased by 5.09% from 2014. All information calls decreased by 15.5% but HCF information calls increased 2.67%, and while medication identification requests (Drug ID) decreased 31.7%, human exposures reported to PCs were essentially flat, increasing by 0.149%. Human exposures with less serious outcomes have decreased 2.95% per year since 2008 while those with more serious outcomes (moderate, major or death) have increased by 4.34% per year since 2000. The top 5 substance classes most frequently involved in all human exposures were analgesics (11.1%), household cleaning substances (7.54%), cosmetics/personal care products (7.41%), sedatives/hypnotics/antipsychotics (5.83%), and antidepressants (4.58%). Sedative/Hypnotics/Antipsychotics exposures as a class increased the most rapidly (2597 calls (11.4%)/year) over the last 14 years for cases showing more serious outcomes. The top 5 most common exposures in children age 5 years or less were cosmetics/ personal care products (13.6%), household cleaning substances (11.2%), analgesics (9.12%), foreign bodies/toys/miscellaneous (6.45%), and topical preparations (5.33%). Drug identification requests comprised 35.0% of all information calls. Database documented 1831 human exposures resulting in death with 1371 human fatalities judged related (RCF of 1-Undoubtedly responsible, 2-Probably responsible, or 3-Contributory). Conclusions: These data support the continued value of PC expertise and need for specialized medical toxicology information to manage more serious exposures, despite a decrease in calls involving less serious exposures. Unintentional and intentional exposures continue to be a significant cause of morbidity and mortality. The near real-time, always current status of database represents a national public health resource to collect and monitor exposure cases and information calls. The continuing mission of database is to provide a nationwide infrastructure for surveillance for all types of exposures (e.g., foreign body, viral, bacterial, venomous, chemical agent, or commercial product), the identification of events of public health significance, resilience, response and situational awareness tracking. Database is a model system for the real-time surveillance of national and global public health. Even as it was administered, this year's flu shot was unusually painful to me. At the time, I thought that perhaps the pain I felt was still within the normal range and may have been caused by the particular combination of chemicals in this years vaccine. After I received the flu shot, I headed back to work. Within 3-4 hours, I was in extreme pain whenever I tried to use my left arm. I remember audibly gasping in pain multiple times when I unthinkingly moved my left arm while meeting with my undergraduate research assistant that afternoon.  The pain continued, and I continued to brush it off as just an inconvenience that will surely go away soon. My first suspicion that something might be wrong was when my husband, son, and mother-in-law, all of whom received the flu shot a few days after I did, were, unlike me, all feeling fine and reporting no pain. It also gave me pause when my daughter, who had received the flu shot a few days before I did and had mentioned a sore arm afterwards, was astonished at the level of pain I was feeling even several days after receiving the shot. A week after I had received the flu shot, the pain was still there and even getting worse instead of better. At that point I decided that this cannot be within the normal range. I called the ask-a-nurse hotline to learn what I should be doing or not doing to help my arm start to heal. I was not sure if I should put ice packs or hot pads on my arm, and I was not sure if it would be better to try to move it despite the pain or to avoid moving it. The nurse advised me to contact my physician. I immediately called my internist's office asking for advice. They called me back later and advised me to take pain killers and to call them again after two weeks if the pain still persisted by then. I soon discovered that I could not wait that long. The pain became debilitating, and I became scared that I might suffer a permanent loss of functioning in my arm.  A couple of days after calling my internist, I asked my husband to call a friend who is a physician for further advice. He suggested that I see an orthopedist. The next morning, I went into the walk-in orthopedics clinic and saw an orthopedist. He prescribed Celebrex, a strong anti-inflammatory medication for 1-2 months maximum because of concerns about my liver functioning, given that I am already on another medication (Methimazole for Graves' disease) that could damage my liver. Celebrex helped with the pain, but I could not take it for more than a month because it gave me headaches so severe that they caused me to wake up in pain. Sometimes the headaches caused me to have to leave work and seek rest in bed in a dark room in the middle of the day. These headaches were worrisome to me because, normally, I rarely have headaches at all. When I stopped taking Celebrex, the headaches stopped, but the pain in my left shoulder returned the very next day and was worse than ever. Shortly after I stopped taking Celebrex, I saw my internist for an annual exam. I mentioned to her that I was really worried about the worsening pain in my shoulder. Because of the pain, I was unable to sleep through the night, had to enlist my husband for help in dressing myself and was even struggling to drive. These disruptions to my life were making me wonder if I should just go back to taking the Celebrex despite the headaches it gave me. She examined me and determined that I probably had a rotator cuff injury. She recommended that I see a physical therapist and switch back to over-the counter pain killers. I immediately scheduled sessions with a physical therapist. The first couple of sessions were fine, but after the fourth visit, the pain in my shoulder was worse. When I again found that I was in more pain after my fifth visit, I visited the orthopedist for another appointment. He advised me to stop the physical therapy since it had not helped and to have an MRI to find out what was going on. The MRI results showed edema in the hume

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The shot was administered very high on my arm, almost at the joint, and I felt the vaccine flow down my arm. Since onset, the pain has continued in varying degrees of severity. Sometimes it is just an ache, other times it makes it impossible to lift my arm in certain directions, grasp items, turn or roll over without strong pain throughout shoulder and/or arm. I have tried resting it, warm compresses, massage and gentle yoga in addition to pain meds. Everything I have tried only works temporarily, and often the pain returns worse the next day after gentle exercise or massage. I am seeing my GP tomorrow to discuss the matter.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was feeling very lightheaded and "floaty" in the early evening while I was watching TV.  Got up to get to the kitchen and remembered that I had my vaccinations--influenza and pneumonia (in Left Thigh)--thigh was sore.  About 8:30 realized I was maybe having a slight reaction to the vaccine, typical, so took a shower and readied for bed.  While in shower, back muscles started spasming and cramping.  Almost immediately got chills and realized I actually had a fever.  Went to bed.  Pain in leg was immense, moving or covers touching it woke me up.  Fever, cramping, and chills continued through the night and continued the next day, continuing to get worse as Saturday progressed.  Saturday afternoon, got off work and got home.  Overwhelmed by exhaustion.  Took 800mg ibuprofin and went to sleep.  Woke 2 hours later, had to crawl down stairs pain in leg was incapacitating.  Could not walk without hanging on to walls.  Fever, chills, body aches continued to the next day.  Sunday the fever was mostly gone and I felt much more myself, but could not move leg normally.  I could not stand even brushing anywhere on my entire thigh muscle, and a rash appeared right above my inner knee.  Ibuprofin useless.  My pain scale is such: 10, migraine.  9: this pain in my leg 8: childbirth.  As of today, wednesday the 11th, my leg is still very tender, but I"m able to both gently touch it and move my foot normally while walking.  I still walk with a limp, and my thigh feels extremely stiff and tight.  After the tenderness dissipates a little, I will start doing some light stretches as I honestly worry I may lose some range of motion if I don't.  This was very unpleasant.  But I guess if I don't get pneumonia again--maybe don't get pneumonia TWICE again--it will be worth it.
HISTORY: Sensitivity to DPT vaccine.  It was assumed to be due to Tetanus.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the flu shot Oct. 3. I started having headaches approximately 2 1/2 weeks later. On October 31st 1/2 of my tongue felt odd on the way home from work and I had a severe headache almost enough to pull over and vomit. I got home and went to bed and woke up at 9:30 am the next morning unable to close my right eye and my right side of my face drooped and a horrid headache. I thought I was having an aneurysm or stroke so I called 911. After blood work and a CT Scan I was DX with bells palsy. I  was started on  an antiviral and prednisone and given Norco 5/325mg. I returned to work about 10 days later after following up with an ENT and my primary Dr.  I continued to have increasing symptons. Numbness in my left arm and tingling and jolts down my left arm. My pulse would run up into the 130's and my BP up into the 140/96. My BP is normally 115/70. While I was at work on Nov 27th,  I felt my heart racing and my left arm ached and felt numb so I went up to the nurses station and they took my blood pressure. 70/40 is the last I heard and then woke up on the nurses station floor with a code team around me and pads attached had I needed shocked. I was taken down to the ER and told I just had a syncope episode and sent home. Headaches continued as well as the numbness and my left arm. I believe on the 17th of December my right arm started to go numb and the chest pains and severe headaches continued so I went to the ER and was admitted for a stroke workup. 3 days later I was discharged with no answers. My Primary Dr had let me know I had a vitamin b12 deficiency, my level is 232 and should be up around 450. Vit B12 deficiency has a lot of the symptoms I have been experiencing.  So I started a supplement. Now the question is why am i deficient A. Stomach stapled = No B. Bowel surgery = No C. Autoimmune disease stirred up by something viral that could have caused the bells palsy and this deficiency. So I am now taking a Vitamin B supplement and continue to take  nortriptoline for nerve pain. All of this...from the Flu shot.
LAB_DATA: CT SCAN BLOOD WORK CT SCANS WITH CONTRAST MRI WITH AND WITHOUT CONTRAST SPINAL TAP

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This spontaneous report was received from a pharmacist and refers to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient had no pertinent medical history and no drug reactions/allergies. There were no concomitant medications. On 22-SEP-2016, the patient was vaccinated with a dose of PNEUMOVAX23 lot # M027552 with an expiration date: 04-FEB-2018 for prophylaxis (dose, route of vaccination and anatomical location were not reported). On 23-SEP-2016, reported as about one day after receiving the vaccine, the patient experienced cellulitis, swelling and inflammation about 2 inches below the injection site. The patient sought medical attention and visited pharmacist. The patient was directed to take unspecified antihistamine medication and put ice on his arm. No lab diagnostics studies were performed. The outcome of cellulitis, inflammation and swelling was unknown. The relatedness between the events and vaccination with PNEUMOVAX23 was not reported. Upon internal review cellulitis was determined to be medically significant. This is one of two reports from the same source. Follow up information has been received from the pharmacist on 25-OCT-2016, who stated that the patient was a 17 years old female. Also, the pharmacist mentioned that the patient was vaccinated on 22-SEP-2016 at 14:40 with a first dose of PNEUMOVAX23 on her right deltoid, intramuscularly. Furthermore, the pharmacist stated the onset date of the events was 22-SEP-2016 (previosly reported as: 23-SEP-2016) and the patient recovered from all the adverse events on 24-SEP-2016. Follow up information has been received on 10-JAN-2017. An investigation into the manufacture of lot M027552 was completed and confirmed that all in-process quality checks were satisfactory. The results indicated that the lot was manufactured in accordance with manufacturing site standard operating procedures. The lot was confirmed to have met the requirements for market release. Following medical review of the AE report and the Quality investigation, there were no identified concerns related to quality within the results of the investigation. Additional information is not expected because all scheduled follow-up was received. Product and narrative were updated.; Sender's Comments: US-009507513-1609USA014340:, MERCK 1609USA013332:Mfr number.

This spontaneous report was received from a nurse practitioner concerning a 24 year old female patient. The patient's pertinent medical history, drug reactions or allergies and concomitant medications were not reported. Approximately in 2007, 2008 and 2013 (reported as "at age 15 years, 16 years and 21 years"), the patient received a complete series of properly stored GARDASIL injection (dose, route and site of administration, lot # and expiration date were not provided) as vaccination against papillomavirus. In approximately 2014, reported as "2 and 1/2 years ago", the patient experienced myeloblastic lymphocytic leukemia. On an unknown date, she developed two genital warts and had a Papanicolaou (Pap) test that showed human papillomavirus (HPV), which was "not the type of high risk for neoplasm". The patient sought medical attention and received unspecified "chemotherapy type" treatment for myeloblastic lymphocytic leukemia. Product quality complaint was not involved. At the time of reporting, the patient's myeloblastic lymphocytic leukemia was in remission since an unknown date. The outcome of the event of HPV infection was not reported. The relatedness between the events of myeloblastic lymphocytic leukemia and HPV infection and the vaccination with GARDASIL was not reported. Upon internal review, myeloblastic lymphocytic leukemia was considered to be medically significant.  Follow-up information has been received from the reporting nurse practitioner on 06-JAN-2017. The patient's concurrent conditions included seizure disorder. Concomitant medications included unspecified anti-seizure medication. The patient recovered from genital warts (on an unknown date) without treatment and had no recurrence. The nurse practitioner was not able to provide any further information as she was not in her office at the time of the call. The reporter also stated that she did not think that myeloblastic leukemia or lymphocytic leukemia was related to GARDASIL. Additional information is not expected. Company Causality Assessment: Based on the limited information currently available for this case, a reasonable possibility to suggest a relationship between the GARDASIL and the reported events cannot be established. Is pending important information about the patient's pertinent medical history,concurrent conditions and concomitant medications. also is important that the patient recovered from genital warts  without treatment and had no recurrence. Company Comment- No changes to the GARDASIL safety information are warranted at this time.  Merck and Co., Inc., known as MSD, continues to monitor the safety profile of the GARDASIL.; Sender's Comments: MERCK 1611USA013477:Mfr number.

Case number PHEH2015US023166, is an initial spontaneous report received from a nurse on 06 Nov 2015. This report refers to an adult female patient of an unknown age. Past medical history and concomitant medications were not reported. The patient was vaccinated with FLUVIRIN (batch number: not reported) at a dose of 0.5 ml intramuscularly on an unknown date in Dec 2012 at 12:00 PM. On the same day shortly after vaccination (minute after vaccination), the patient had an allergic responses to FLUVIRIN. The patient experienced itching, numbness around the mouth and she felt like her throat was closing. The patient did not experience urticaria. The patient was treated with BENADRYL and the symptoms resolved the same day, before the patient left the clinic. It was stated that, the patient received FLUVIRIN again in 2014 and 2015 at an allergists office with no difficulty and allergic reaction did not occur again. Upon follow up, it was stated that the patient experienced itchy palms and red rash on an unknown date. Reporter did not think that the patient had any other allergies. The outcome of the events hypersensitivity, throat tightness, hypoaesthesia oral and pruritus was reported as complete recovery (resolved) on an unknown date in 2012 and complete recovery on an unknown date for other events. Seriousness of the events hypersensitivity, throat tightness, hypoaesthesia oral and pruritus was reported as non serious and not reported for other events. The causality of the events was not reported. The seriousness assessment of the events was upgraded to medically significant based on information available in the source document. Following an internal review was done on 25 Nov 2015 for the information received on 06 Nov 2015: Seriousness of the event throat tightness was upgraded to medically significant. Follow up report received from a nurse on 01 Dec 2015: Added events (allergic response and numbness around the mouth) and outcome of events. Follow up report received from a nurse on 28 Dec 2015: Added events cold sores and red rash and updated patient details (date of birth) and suspect drug information (dose and time of dose). Follow up report received from a nurse on 20 Jan 2016: Deleted the event cold sores (oral herpes) as the patient did not experience this event.

On 05-JAN-2017, the patient was vaccinated with GARDASIL for prevention of Human Papillomavirus (HPV), M-M-R II for prevention of measles, mumps and rubella and hepatitis a vaccine, inactivated (Manufacturer unknown) (dosing details were not reported) for prevention of Hepatitis A. On the same day, after the vaccines were administered, the patient stiffened up, fell over and was unresponsive. The patient was taken to the emergency room at an unspecified hospital. There were unspecified tests and blood work performed (results not reported). It was unknown if any treatment was provided for the adverse events. On the same day, the patient recovered. Reporting physician had not assessed the causality of the events with respect to the suspect vaccines. Upon internal review, the event, unresponsive to stimuli was considered to be medically significant. Additional information has been requested.

This is a Literature report. This author reported similar reports for 2 subjects. This is the first of two reports. This author conducted an open-label, multicenter, randomized, comparative study evaluated immunogenicity, safety and tolerability of concomitant (Group 1; n=330) vs. non-concomitant (Group 2; n=323) VAQTATM (25 U/0.5 mL) (hepatitis A vaccine; HAV) with PROQUAD (measles/mumps/rubella/varicella; MMRV) and PREVNAR (7-valent pneumococcal; PCV-7) in healthy, 12-23 month-old children. Group 1 received HAV/MMRV/PCV-7 concomitantly on Day 1 and second doses of HAV/MMRV at Week 24. Group 2 received MMRV/PCV-7 on Day 1, HAV at Weeks 6 and 30 and MMRV at Week 34. A subject of an unspecified age, race, and gender received on Day 1 pneumococcal 13-valent conjugate vaccine (diphtheria crm197 protein) (PREVENAR) and measles, mumps, rubella, and varicella vaccine (PROQUAD); both via an unspecified route of administration on an unknown date at a single doses for immunization. At week 6 of study, the patient also received hepatitis a vaccine (VAQTATM, 25 U/0.5 mL) via an unspecified route of administration on an unknown date at a single dose for immunization. The subject's medical history and concomitant medications were not provided. On an unknown date, on day 52 of study, the patient experienced dehydration and gastroenteritis, which were serious for being medically significant. The clinical outcome of the serious adverse events, dehydration and gastroenteritis, was unknown. The author reported the serious adverse events dehydration and gastroenteritis (Group 2 post-administration of MMRV/PCV-7) possibly vaccine-related.; Sender's Comments: The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety valuation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was tired all day.  During dinner he was fine and eating.  Right after finishing his dinner he started convulsing (grand mal) in his high chair.  911 was called immediately and he was transported to the emergency room.  He was given medicine to control his fever.  The next day he had a follow up Doctor appointment. He had a seizure 6-21-16 which resulted in a 911 call, hospital visit, dr visit and neurologist visit.  The neurologist did an EEG and an overnight EEG. On 8*11*2016 he had another seizure 911 was called and he went to the emergency room.  He was in the pool swimming with family, and he turned blue. He needed x rays taken to determine whether or not he had fluid in his lungs. The neurologist determined he has Epilepsy.  He takes medication 2x per day.  Epilepsy is commonly a hereditary disease, but it is not found in either mom or dad's family.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I did not feel the shot when I got it. In 2 hours it felt like a bee sting. There was no redness, but it was painful. Approximately 3 weeks later, the pain spread further down my arm to just above my right elbow. My right shoulder blade also was painful. About the 5 week point, I started to feel like the area where I got the shot was hot and swollen. I also started to have a lot of pain in my thumb and a burn in my shoulder. The Nurse Advice line advised me to go to Urgent Care because there were no appointments available at the health Clinic. The Urgent Care doctor only gave me KENALOG to apply to my arm. I reported this treatment to the Health Clinic. They advised me to go to the ER. The ER doctor X-Rayed my arm and prescribed me SOMA and hydrocodone. The diagnosis was shoulder pain (Deltoid area) of Unknown cause. I am currently in Physical therapy.
